{"type":"message-part","timestamp":"2026-06-12T07:53:12.209Z","messageId":"b5c4820d-3cbd-4b2a-8a9f-224c289c3fd6","role":"user","index":1,"part":{"type":"text","text":"# Wide-to-Long Stocks Multi-Line Chart with Vega-Altair `transform_fold`\n\n## Background\n\nA common analytics task is to plot several time series whose values live in separate columns (wide form) as a single multi-line chart. Vega-Altair exposes the `transform_fold` transform that reshapes wide-form data into long form directly inside the chart specification, so you do not have to pre-melt the DataFrame in pandas.\n\nIn this task you will build a small wide-form pandas DataFrame of monthly stock prices for three companies and use `transform_fold` to reshape it to long form inside the spec, then render it as a multi-line chart and save the result as a self-contained HTML file.\n\n## Requirements\n\n* Construct the source data **inside `build_chart.py`** as a wide-form `pandas.DataFrame` with exactly these four columns and at least 12 rows (one row per monthly observation):\n  * `Date` (a date / datetime-like value, e.g. monthly timestamps).\n  * `AAPL` (numeric price).\n  * `AMZN` (numeric price).\n  * `GOOG` (numeric price).\n    Do **not** load this data from `vega_datasets` or any external file – the point of the task is to demonstrate `transform_fold` on wide-form data you provide.\n* Build a single Vega-Altair chart that:\n  * Uses the wide-form DataFrame as the chart data source.\n  * Applies `transform_fold` to fold the three price columns into long form, using `as_=['company', 'price']` so the long-form fields are named `company` and `price`.\n  * Renders a line mark (`mark_line`) with one line per company.\n  * Encodes `Date` on the x axis as a temporal field.\n  * Encodes the folded `price` on the y axis as a quantitative field.\n  * Encodes the folded `company` on color as a nominal field, producing a legend that lists `AAPL`, `AMZN`, and `GOOG`.\n* Save the chart to `/home/user/myproject/chart.html` via `chart.save(...)` as a self-contained HTML file that loads Vega-Lite/Vega-Embed and renders the chart in a browser.\n\n## Implementation Hints\n\n* You can construct the DataFrame with any reasonable monthly date range (e.g. `pandas.date_range(..., freq='MS')`) and any plausible monthly price values – exact values do not matter, only the schema and number of rows.\n* Pass the wide DataFrame directly to `alt.Chart(...)`; let `transform_fold` reshape it inside the spec rather than pre-melting with pandas.\n* Remember that after folding, the new long-form fields are the ones you name in `as_`; encode the y/color channels against those names, not against the original wide column names.\n* Make sure the chart is saved as a real HTML file (not a JSON spec) so it can be opened directly in a browser.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n* Project path: /home/user/myproject\n* Command: python3 build\\_chart.py\n* The command must produce `/home/user/myproject/chart.html` containing a renderable Vega-Lite specification.\n* The embedded Vega-Lite specification must:\n  * Use `mark` of type `line` (a string `\"line\"` or an object `{\"type\": \"line\", ...}`).\n  * Include a `transform` entry of the form `{\"fold\": [...], \"as\": [...]}` where the `fold` array equals `[\"AAPL\", \"AMZN\", \"GOOG\"]` (in that order) and the `as` array equals `[\"company\", \"price\"]`.\n  * Encode `x` with `field == \"Date\"` and `type == \"temporal\"`.\n  * Encode `y` with `field == \"price\"` and `type == \"quantitative\"`.\n  * Encode `color` with `field == \"company\"` and `type == \"nominal\"`.\n* Browser verification: Loading `chart.html` in a browser must render the chart without JavaScript console errors. The rendered chart must show exactly three colored lines, and the color legend must list the three series `AAPL`, `AMZN`, and `GOOG`."}}
